  },

  "resilience_assessment": {
    "failure_modes": [
      {
        "scenario": "A: Fraud detection service returns 503 for 5 minutes",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTION: Every payment request will wait up to 2s for the fraud service, receive a 503, then fail. With 20 workers and 2s timeout, the service can churn through ~10 failed requests/second. If inbound rate exceeds 10 req/s, requests queue up and eventually all workers are blocked. No circuit breaker means ALL 300 seconds of the outage produce latency-impacted failures — the service never fast-fails. SURVIVABILITY: The service stays up but is functionally dead for payments. 100% payment failure rate for 5 minutes. If request rate is high, worker thread exhaustion causes cascading failure to non-payment endpoints too. MUST ADD: Circuit breaker on fraud detection (e.g., 3-failure threshold, 30s reset). Consider a fallback policy — can low-risk payments proceed without fraud check? Add a bulkhead to isolate fraud-check thread usage from other operations."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "B: Database connection pool exhaustion for 30 seconds",
        "handling": "unhandled",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTION: All 10 DB connections are occupied. New payment requests that pass fraud + Stripe successfully will fail on the DB write step. CRITICAL RISK: Stripe has already charged the customer but the transaction record is not persisted. This creates ghost charges — money taken, no record in the system. With no connection retry, every DB write fails immediately during the 30s window. Additionally, any endpoint touching the DB (health checks, dashboards, status queries) also fails — potential for load balancer to mark the instance unhealthy and pull it from rotation. SURVIVABILITY: SERVICE SURVIVES but DATA INTEGRITY IS COMPROMISED. Payments charged to Stripe with no corresponding DB record. Recovery requires manual Stripe reconciliation. MUST ADD: (1) Connection retry with short backoff (2) Increase pool to at least match worker count (20) (3) Implement a transactional outbox or ensure Stripe charge and DB write are coordinated — charge Stripe AFTER reserving a DB connection, or use idempotency keys for safe retry (4) Connection pool wait timeout with explicit error rather than hanging."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "C: Stripe API latency increases to 8s for 10 minutes",
        "handling": "partial",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTION: Each Stripe call takes 8s (within the 10s timeout, so no timeout errors). With 20 workers and 8s per request, effective throughput = 20/8 = 2.5 payments/second. If inbound rate exceeds 2.5 req/s, worker threads saturate. But the fraud check adds another 0-2s per request, so effective per-request time is 8-10s, meaning throughput is 2-2.5 req/s. The circuit breaker does NOT trip because requests succeed — they're just slow. Over 10 minutes, thread pool saturation causes unbounded request queuing. SURVIVABILITY: SERVICE DEGRADES SEVERELY. No errors are thrown, but latency balloons and throughput craters. From the user's perspective, payments hang for 8-10 seconds. From the system's perspective, all 20 workers are consumed, and any non-payment traffic sharing these workers is starved. The circuit breaker is useless here because there are no failures. MUST ADD: (1) Latency-based circuit breaker or adaptive timeout (trip if p99 > 5s) (2) Request queuing with bounded queue and shed policy (3) Separate thread pools for payment vs non-payment work (bulkhead) (4) Client-visible timeout shorter than server timeout (e.g., 5s client timeout even though Stripe gets 10s)."
      },
      {
        "scenario": "D: Network partition to Stripe for 2 minutes",
        "handling": "partial",
        "recommendation": "PREDICTION: Stripe calls will timeout after 10s each. First 5 timeouts trip the circuit breaker (~50s into the outage). Circuit opens — subsequent requests fast-fail for 60s. At 110s, circuit enters half-open, sends a probe request which also fails (partition still active for another 10s). Circuit re-opens for another 60s. Partition heals at 120s but circuit stays open until ~170s mark. TOTAL IMPACT: ~2 minutes of outage + ~50s of unnecessary fast-fail after partition heals = ~170s of payment failures. During the first 50s before circuit opens, 5 requests block for 10s each, consuming 50 worker-seconds. SURVIVABILITY: SERVICE SURVIVES. The circuit breaker does its job after the initial 5-failure warmup. The main risk is (1) the 50s warmup period where workers are blocked on 10s timeouts and (2) the circuit staying open for ~50s after the partition heals. SHOULD ADD: (1) Lower circuit breaker threshold to 3 failures to trip faster (2) Reduce Stripe timeout to 5s to free workers sooner during timeouts (3) Implement half-open probing with shorter timeout (4) Queue payments during circuit-open for retry after reset rather than failing immediately."
      }
    ],
    "retry_config": "No retry logic mentioned for any component. DB has no connection retry. Fraud detection has no retry. Stripe retries not mentioned — relying solely on circuit breaker. For a payment service, at minimum idempotent retries with exponential backoff should exist for transient Stripe errors.",
    "timeout_config": "Fraud: 2s (reasonable). Stripe: 10s (too high — causes severe thread pool pressure under slow-latency scenarios). No end-to-end request timeout mentioned — a request could theoretically take 2s (fraud) + 10s (stripe) + DB time = 12+ seconds with no overall cap.",
